== Otto von Below ==
Otto Ernst Vinzent Leo von Below (18 January 1857 – 9 March 1944) was a Prussian [General der Infanterie](/General_of_the_Infantry_(Germany)) who served in the [Imperial German Army](/German_Army_(German_Empire)) during the [First World War](/World_War_I). He is best known for his command, alongside Austro‑Hungarian commander [Svetozar Borojević](/Svetozar_Borojevi%C4%87), during the [Battle of Caporetto](/Battle_of_Caporetto) in October–November 1917.

Pre‑war
Von Below was born in [Danzig](/Gda%C5%84sk). &#91;2&#93;
He was promoted [Generalmajor](/Generalmajor) in 1909 and [Generalleutnant](/Generalleutnant) in 1912. Since April 1912, he commanded the [2nd Infantry Division](/2nd_Division_(German_Empire)).

First World War
Eastern Front
On 1 August 1914, at the [outbreak of the First World War](/July_Crisis), Below was given command of [I Reserve Corps](/I_Reserve_Corps_(German_Empire)) as part of the [8th Army](/8th_Army_(German_Empire)) on the [Eastern Front](/Eastern_Front_(World_War_I)). &#91;3&#93; He led his Corps in the Battles of [Gumbinnen](/Battle_of_Gumbinnen), [Tannenberg](/Battle_of_Tannenberg_(1914)), and the [First Battle of the Masurian Lakes](/First_Battle_of_the_Masurian_Lakes). As a result of his successes, he was promoted to [General der Infanterie](/General_of_the_Infantry_(Germany)) &#91;4&#93; at the end of August 1914 and to command of 8th Army at the beginning of November 1914. &#91;5&#93;

Below commanded the 8th Army in the [Second Battle of the Masurian Lakes](/Second_Battle_of_the_Masurian_Lakes) (February 1915) and the [Army of the Niemen](/Army_of_the_Niemen) (later renamed 8th Army) in the Courland Offensive (May 1915). His forces advanced into [Courland](/Courland) and [Lithuania](/Lithuania) as far as the southern reaches of the [Western Dvina River](/Daugava_River). &#91;1&#93;

Macedonia
In October 1916, Below was appointed to the command of [Heeresgruppe Below](/Heeresgruppe_Below) &#91;6&#93; on the [Macedonian Front](/Macedonian_front), consisting of the [German 11th Army](/11th_Army_(German_Empire)) and the [First](/First_Army_(Bulgaria)) & [Second](/Second_Army_(Bulgaria)) Bulgarian Armies. &#91;7&#93; In April 1917, he was briefly sent to the [Western Front](/Western_Front_(World_War_I)) to command [6th Army](/6th_Army_(German_Empire)) &#91;8&#93; around [Lille](/Lille). &#91;9&#93;

Italy
Below next served on the [Italian Front](/Italian_Campaign_(World_War_I)) from September 1917. Commanding the Austro‑German [14th Army](/14th_Army_(German_Empire)) &#91;10&#93; (seven German and ten [Austro-Hungarian](/Austro-Hungarian_Army) divisions) in the [Battle of Caporetto](/Battle_of_Caporetto), his units were able to break into the [Italian](/Kingdom_of_Italy) front line and rout the Italian army, which had practically no mobile reserves. The battle was a demonstration of the effectiveness of the use of [stormtroopers](/Stormtroopers_(Imperial_Germany)) and the [infiltration tactics](/Infiltration_tactics) developed in part by [Oskar von Hutier](/Oskar_von_Hutier). The use of [poison gas](/Poison_gas) by German troops played a key role in the collapse of the [Italian Second Army](/Italian_Second_Army). &#91;11&#93; A breakdown in German logistics brought the battle to a close on the line of the [Piave River](/Piave_River) and the front soon froze again in [trench warfare](/Trench_warfare).

Western Front
In February 1918, Below was brought back to the Western Front to command the new [17th Army](/17th_Army_(German_Empire)) for the [Kaiserschlacht](/Kaiserschlacht) Offensive. &#91;10&#93; Below was expected to overrun [Arras](/Arras) during March 1918 in a repeat of Caporetto; his inability to do so led to the failure of the German campaign to capture the [Somme](/Somme_(river)) that same month. &#91;9&#93; Attacking the stronger, better prepared British [Third Army](/Third_Army_(United_Kingdom)), he had less success than forces further south facing the British [Fifth Army](/Fifth_Army_(United_Kingdom)).

In January 1918, he made the following revolutionary proposal to [Ludendorff](/Erich_Ludendorff): "Forget about the offensive and shorten the front lines as much as necessary; build Panzers throughout all of 1918 and, with your Panzer squadrons, break through all the way to the Channel coast in the Spring of 1919". Below briefly commanded the [1st Army](/1st_Army_(German_Empire)). &#91;12&#93; Shortly before the war's end, Below was involved in preparations for a possible final battle on German territory (Home Defense Forces West). &#91;4&#93;

Awards
Below was awarded the [Pour le Mérite](/Pour_le_M%C3%A9rite) on 16 February 1915 "for outstanding leadership and distinguished military planning and successful operations", and the Oakleaves (signifying a second award) on 27 April 1917. &#91;13&#93; Below was also awarded the [Order of the Black Eagle](/Order_of_the_Black_Eagle) on 1 November 1917 and the [Iron Cross](/Iron_Cross), 1st and 2nd class. &#91;4&#93;

Post‑war
Below retired in 1919. A post‑war attempt by the [Allies](/Allied_Powers_of_World_War_II) to try him as a [war criminal](/War_criminal) failed. &#91;4&#93; Otto von Below died on 9 March 1944 in Besenhausen near [Göttingen](/G%C3%B6ttingen).

Family
Below was a cousin of [Fritz von Below](/Fritz_von_Below), another German commander during the war. The two Generals are often confused.

